We tried that for the first time yesterday afternoon and it was fairly good=
 and reliable.
Since I don't want to be accused of being some sort of search engine hacker=
, let's start by talking about the kind of headlines that catch people's at=
tention. But, I agree with you that there are times when quality is annoyin=
gly poor.
Reception seems to vary with the number of users logged into Skype.
There's a second issue here too. A kitten was just killed and IBM did it.
I told her to delete that post, because it made her look like a potential p=
redator or molester. I have to admit that I hate articles with titles like =
"The coolest gadget you've ever used" or "Huh? Did I convince you to  pay m=
ore attention to your page titles, your Web site title, and your blog or ar=
ticle titles?
What's your opinion of this issue?
One was "Against RSS". Today at about the same time, there was a paltry 5 m=
illion and reception was fairly good.
The reason that titles are so darn important is because of how we scan info=
rmation and make snap decisions on whether to dig into a story further or n=
ot.
But, I agree with you that there are times when quality is annoyingly poor.=
 I told her to delete that post, because it made her look like a potential =
predator or molester.
Just got off the, um, headset from a conference call that we enabled via th=
e popular Skype service, and I have to say that the voice quality just stun=
k.
If they could, companies would probably like to have previous years Annual =
Reports vanish in a puff of smoke after 12 months too, leaving just a thin =
sheaf of financial data and legalese.
The answer's more simple: Don is no longer an IBM employee so it makes no l=
ogical sense for his weblog to remain accessible on the ibm.
If you were scanning a musician's weblog, for example, wouldn't you find an=
 article entitled "The dirt on my new studio recording" far more interestin=
g than "Finished up the new CD"?
On the other hand, if there are specific words in your marketplace lexicon =
that are considered high engagement, I would definitely encourage you to us=
e them  at least once in a while. WRAPPING THINGS UPOkay, so you've given m=
e five minutes of your time.
Robert goes quite a bit further, though, stating that he believes that all =
blogs are sacrosanct and shouldn't be deleted. I have deleted a couple of p=
osts from my blog. Knowing which is most popular and then using that as par=
t of your titles helps people recognize your material.
Do you find that the voice quality is good, "good enough", excellent, or do=
 you just skip using it for any sort of serious conversation? I have delete=
d a couple of posts from my blog.
It may seem like I'm just talking about blogging, but what we'll consider i=
s generally true of any written material, online or off. It was worse than =
bad cellphone coverage in an noisy room, and both of us had high-speed conn=
ections and good audio equipment.
But at the time I felt it was appropriate. I told her to delete that post, =
because it made her look like a potential predator or molester. He has been=
 published over a thousand times, launched four Internet-relatedstartup com=
panies, has written twenty business and technical books and holds both an M=
BA and MS Ed.
TARGETING THE SEARCH ENGINESProbably more important with the difference bet=
ween "cellphone" and "cell phone" than human readers is search engine resul=
ts, actually. I find that a bit puzzling, but perhaps that explains why his=
 Scobleizer blog was never hosted at Microsoft while he was an employee: pe=
rhaps he expected that once he left they'd shut it down? It may seem like I=
'm just talking about blogging, but what we'll consider is generally true o=
f any written material, online or off.
Given that, what's to be made of Robert Scoble's complaint about IBM wiping=
 a few weblogs out of its system? com blogger was writing racist, sexist or=
 similar vitriol, the company would be liable and suffer the consequences t=
oo.
Given the network conditions, I expected poor performance and possibly for =
it to be completely unusable.
One suggestion would be to consider Google Talk when Skype is crammed.=

