Now my comments:
Please change the blinking red text to something not blinking, 
because I and many other people are not able to read a text 
that constantly disapears...

Instead of
LANG= LC_ALL= ddccontrol -p -c -d
you probably want a:
LC_ALL=C ddccontrol -p -c -d

otherwise an LC_MÑMESSAGES=pt_BR does not get overwritteny an 
empty LC_ALL.

0x02: I switched it to 1 with the order to write a 2, now it 
got stuck with 1. Any ideas on how to switch it back??

0x04: factory reset: kicks in on writes >= 1 (0 does nothing).

0x14: switches between the modes. The monitor has five modes
I know of. Changing and than reading 0x14 reveals:
sRGB: 1
Text, Picture, Movie: 5
Custom: last value of (2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8, 9) set

but writing does:
0, 7, 10: does not change the value
1: sRGB
2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8, 9: Custom

Writing 1 switches the monitor to sRGB mode in a way the 
monitor knows of. I can see in the menu that we are in sRGB, 
the other numbers change the settings visible (contrast, etc), 
but the monitor switches to Custom in any case.
...by the way, playing here set 0x02 back to 2.



0x60 input setting does not react on 0 or 1, but switches to 
analog (or SUB-D or DVI (analog), I don't know) when told to 
write 2. Actually, the DDC/CI seems to work only on the 
selected input, that means after writing 2, I can't set it back 
with the digital input...

0xc0 is the on-time in hours and it's read only (doesn't change 
on set). That is like the km-counter in a car...

0x87, 0xb6, 0xdf seem read-only, too.



Bye,
	Robert


